ish, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzWilliam , of Hurworth was born about 1155, in Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, William FitzWaltheof , of Hurworth, was 27 and his mother, Mrs. William FitzWaltheof, was 18. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. William FitzWilliam of Hurworth. He died in 1200, in Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"abt 1155–by 1200":"umbes 1155–1200","1155–1200":"1155–1200","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","1181–1235":"1181–1235","1187–1256":"1